## Remarks  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-102"><xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> es el objeto principal que implementa la tecnología de semántica en System.Speech.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-102"><xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> is the primary object that implements the semantic technology in System.Speech.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="c04af-103">Interpretación semántica permite definir reglas para su uso por un motor de reconocimiento para interpretar correctamente la entrada de audio de las gramáticas.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-103">Semantic interpretation allows grammars to define rules for use by a recognition engine to correctly interpret audio input.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="c04af-104">Interpretación semántica también permite que los motores de reconocimiento organizar sus resultados para que pueden procesarse más fácilmente, en lugar de devolver sólo reconoce las palabras y las secuencias de palabras.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-104">Semantic interpretation also enables recognition engines to organize their results so that they can be more easily processed, rather than returning only recognized words and sequences of words.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-105">Por ejemplo, el motor de reconocimiento de salida "Cambiar fondo a rojo" tendría que se puede analizar e interprete por una aplicación antes de que puede actuar.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-105">For example, the recognition engine output "Change background to red" would have to be parsed and interpreted by an application before it could be acted upon.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="c04af-106">Un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar> objeto puede especificar una interpretación semántica para agilizar el procesamiento sea más clara especificando que la frase tiene dos subestructuras semánticos, uno para la selección en segundo plano o primer plano (representado por el texto "background") y otra para seleccionar color (representado por el texto "rojo").</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-106">A <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar> object can specify a semantic interpretation to make processing clearer by specifying that the phrase has two semantic substructures, one for selecting background or foreground (represented by the text "background"), and the other for selecting color (represented by the text "red").</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-107">System.Speech representa la semántica de una operación de reconocimiento en un árbol de <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> objetos.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-107">System.Speech represents the semantics of a recognition operation in a tree of <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> objects.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-108">Cada <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instancia incluye lo siguiente:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-108">Each <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instance includes the following:</span></span>  
  
-   <span data-ttu-id="c04af-109">Un <xref:System.Object>, que se accede por medio de la <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Value%2A> propiedad, se utiliza para la instancia de la clave del <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-109">An <xref:System.Object>, accessed by means of the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Value%2A> property, used to key the instance of the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue>.</span></span>  
  
-   <span data-ttu-id="c04af-110">Una medida de la precisión del análisis semántico, devuelto por la <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Confidence%2A> propiedad.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-110">A measure of the accuracy of semantic parsing, returned by the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Confidence%2A> property.</span></span>  
  
-   <span data-ttu-id="c04af-111">Una colección de pares nombre/valor (<xref:System.Collections.Generic.KeyValuePair%602>) de los objetos secundarios, que también son <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instancias.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-111">A collection of name/value pairs (<xref:System.Collections.Generic.KeyValuePair%602>) of child objects, which are also <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instances.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="c04af-112">Nodos secundarios son accesibles a través de la <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> implementación de <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary%602> mediante una clave de búsqueda de cadena y un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instancia, como en el ejemplo siguiente.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-112">Child nodes are accessible through the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> implementation of <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary%602> using a string lookup key and a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instance, as in the following example.</span></span>  
  
    ```csharp  
    foreach (KeyValuePair<String, SemanticValue> child in semantics)   
    {  
      Utils.CreateSemanticsTreeNodes(semanticsNode.Nodes, child.Value, child.Key);  
    }  
    ```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-113">Los motores de reconocimiento según System.Speech proporcionan instancias válidas de <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> para todos los resultados de reconocimiento, incluso para las frases con ninguna estructura semántica explícita.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-113">Recognition engines based on System.Speech provide valid instances of <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> for all output from recognition, even for phrases with no explicit semantic structure.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-114">El <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> de instancia para una frase se obtiene mediante la <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognizedPhrase.Semantics%2A> propiedad en el <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognizedPhrase> objeto (u objetos que heredan de él, como <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognitionResult>).</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-114">The <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instance for a phrase is obtained using the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognizedPhrase.Semantics%2A> property on the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognizedPhrase> object (or objects that inherit from it, such as <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognitionResult>).</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-115"><xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> objetos que se obtienen reconocido frases sin estructura semántico se caracterizan por:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-115"><xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> objects obtained for recognized phrases without semantic structure are characterized by:</span></span>  
  
-   <span data-ttu-id="c04af-116">La falta de elementos secundarios (<xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Count%2A> es 0).</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-116">The lack of children (<xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Count%2A> is 0).</span></span>  
  
-   <span data-ttu-id="c04af-117">La propiedad <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Value%2A> es `null`.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-117">The <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Value%2A> property is `null`.</span></span>  
  
-   <span data-ttu-id="c04af-118">Un nivel de confianza semántica artificial de 1,0 (devuelto por <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Confidence%2A>).</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-118">An artificial semantic confidence level of 1.0 (returned by <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Confidence%2A>).</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-119">Normalmente, las aplicaciones crean <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instancias indirectamente, agregarlos a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar> objetos mediante el uso de <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticResultValue> y <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticResultKey> instancias, junto con <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Choices> y <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.GrammarBuilder> objetos.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-119">Typically, applications create <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instances indirectly, adding them to <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar> objects by using <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticResultValue> and <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticResultKey> instances,  in conjunction with  <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Choices> and <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.GrammarBuilder> objects.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-120">Dirigir la construcción de un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instancia es útil durante la creación de las gramáticas fuertemente tipado.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-120">Direct construction of a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> instance is useful during the creation of strongly-typed grammars.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-121"><xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> implementa el <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary%602>, <xref:System.Collections.Generic.ICollection%601>, y <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable%601> interfaces.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-121"><xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue> implements the <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IDictionary%602>, <xref:System.Collections.Generic.ICollection%601>, and <xref:System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable%601> interfaces.</span></span>  
  
   
  
## Examples  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-122">El ejemplo siguiente muestra un controlador para un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar.SpeechRecognized> evento diseñado para controlar los comandos para cambiar el color de primer plano y fondo.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-122">The following example shows a handler for a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar.SpeechRecognized> event designed to handle commands to change foreground and background color.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-123">El controlador identifica reconocidas frases que no tienen ninguna estructura semántica subyacente al detectar un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Count%2A> de cero y un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Value%2A> de `null`.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-123">The handler identifies recognized phrases that have no underlying semantic structure by detecting a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Count%2A> of zero and a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Value%2A> of `null`.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="c04af-124">A continuación, se procesa este resultado de reconocimiento analizando el texto sin formato.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-124">This recognition output is then processed directly by parsing the raw text.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-125">En otros casos, el controlador usa las claves para obtener los componentes RGB de un nombre de color, para determinar si el comando cambiará el primer o segundo plano, o para indicar que se ha encontrado ninguna clave válida.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-125">In other cases, the handler uses keys to obtain the RGB components of a color name, to determine whether the command will change the foreground or background, or to indicate that no valid key was found.</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
  
newGrammar.SpeechRecognized +=  
  delegate(object sender, SpeechRecognizedEventArgs eventArgs)   
  {  
  
    // Retrieve the value of the semantic property.  
    bool changeBackGround = true;  
    string errorString = "";  
    SemanticValue semantics = eventArgs.Result.Semantics;  
  
    Color newColor = Color.Empty;  
  
    try   
    {  
      if (semantics.Count == 0 && semantics.Value==null)  
      {  
        // Signifies recognition by a grammar with no semantics.  
        // Parse the string, assuming that the last word is color,  
        // and search for "background" or "foreground" in the input.  
        if (eventArgs.Result.Text.Contains("foreground"))   
        {  
          changeBackGround = false;  
        }  
        string cName = eventArgs.Result.Words[eventArgs.Result.Words.Count - 1].Text;  
        newColor = Color.FromName(cName);  
  
      }  
      else if (semantics.ContainsKey("colorStringList") ^ semantics.ContainsKey("colorRGBValueList"))   
      {  
  
        // Determine whether to change background or foreground.  
        if (semantics.ContainsKey("applyChgToBackground"))   
        {  
          changeBackGround = semantics["applyChgToBackground"].Value is bool;  
        }  
  
        // Get the RGB color value.  
        if (semantics.ContainsKey("colorStringList"))   
        {  
          newColor = Color.FromName((string)semantics["colorStringList"].Value);  
        }  
        if (semantics.ContainsKey("colorRGBValueList"))   
        {  
          newColor = System.Drawing.Color.FromArgb((int)semantics["colorRGBValueList"].Value);  
        }  
      }  
      else   
      {  
  
        // Throw an exception if the semantics do not contain the keys we  
        // support.  
        throw(new Exception("Unsupported semantics keys found."));  
      }  
    }  
  
    catch (Exception exp)   
    {  
      MessageBox.Show(String.Format("Unable to process color semantics.:\n{0}\n", exp.Message));  
      return;  
    }  
  
    // Change colors, either foreground or background.  
    if (changeBackGround)   
    {  
      BackColor = newColor;  
      float Bright = BackColor.GetBrightness();  
      float Hue = BackColor.GetHue();  
      float Sat = BackColor.GetSaturation();  
  
      // Make sure that text is readable regardless of the background.  
      if (BackColor.GetBrightness() <= .50)   
      {  
        ForeColor = Color.White;  
      }  
      else   
      {  
        ForeColor = Color.Black;  
      }  
    }  
    else   
    {  
      ForeColor = newColor;  
      float Bright = ForeColor.GetBrightness();  
      float Hue = ForeColor.GetHue();  
      float Sat = ForeColor.GetSaturation();  
  
      // Make sure that text is readable regardless of Foreground.  
      if (ForeColor.GetBrightness() <= .50)   
      {  
        BackColor = Color.White;  
      }  
      else   
      {  
        BackColor = Color.Black;  
      }  
    }  
    return;  
  };  
```

  
  
## Remarks  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-143">El <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Confidence%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> propiedad, que devuelve una medida de la corrección del análisis semántico, no debe confundirse con el <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognizedPhrase.Confidence%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> propiedad, que devuelve una medida de la precisión del reconocimiento de voz.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-143">The <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Confidence%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property, which returns a measure of the correctness of semantic parsing, should not be confused with the <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.RecognizedPhrase.Confidence%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> property, which returns a measure of the accuracy of speech recognition.</span></span>  
  
   
  
## Examples  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-144">El siguiente ejemplo se utiliza para recorrer de forma recursiva y, a continuación, mostrar información (incluida la confianza) como un <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TreeNodeCollection>, o que los nodos que componen la estructura de árbol de la semántica que se utiliza para identificar una frase.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-144">The following example is used to recursively traverse and then display information (including confidence) as a <xref:System.Windows.Forms.TreeNodeCollection>, or as the nodes making up the tree structure of the semantics used to recognize a phrase.</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
internal static void CreateSemanticsTreeNodes(  
        TreeNodeCollection nodes,  
        SemanticValue semantics,  
        String name)   
{  
  string semanticsText =   
      String.Format("  {0}  (Confidence {1})", name,semantics.Confidence);  
  
  // Format integers as hexadecimal.  
  if (semantics.Value == null )  
  {  
    semanticsText = semanticsText + " = null";  
  }  
  else if (semantics.Value.GetType() == typeof(int))   
  {  
    semanticsText = String.Format("{0} = {1:X} ", semanticsText, semantics.Value);  
  }   
  else   
  {  
    semanticsText = semanticsText + " = " + semantics.Value.ToString();  
  }  
  
  TreeNode semanticsNode = new TreeNode(semanticsText);  
  foreach (KeyValuePair<String, SemanticValue> child in semantics)   
  {  
    CreateSemanticsTreeNodes(semanticsNode.Nodes, child.Value, child.Key);  
  }  
  nodes.Add(semanticsNode);  
}  
```

  
  
## Remarks  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-152">Solo puede tener acceso a datos por valor de clave en tiempo de ejecución, por ejemplo para comprobar *semántico ["myKey"]. Valor*, y esto genera una excepción.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-152">You can only access data by key value at runtime, for example to check *semantic["myKey"].Value*, and this generates an exception.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="c04af-153">Se recomienda que consulta el objeto con <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.ContainsKey%2A> antes de usar <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Item%2A> con una instancia determinada de <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-153">We recommend that you query the object with <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.ContainsKey%2A> before using <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.Item%2A> with a given instance of <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue>.</span></span>  
  
   
  
## Examples  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-154">El ejemplo siguiente muestra un controlador para un <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar.SpeechRecognized> evento diseñado para controlar los comandos para cambiar el color de primer plano y fondo.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-154">The following example shows a handler for a <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.Grammar.SpeechRecognized> event designed to handle commands to change foreground and background color.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="c04af-155">Después de controlar las frases que se reconocen pero no tienen ninguna estructura semántica, el controlador comprueba la presencia de las claves correspondientes mediante <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.ContainsKey%2A> (`applyChgToBackground`, `colorRGBValueList`, o `colorStringList)`y, a continuación, procesa los datos semánticamente organizados.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="c04af-155">After handling phrases that are recognized but have no semantic structure, the handler checks for the presence of appropriate keys using <xref:System.Speech.Recognition.SemanticValue.ContainsKey%2A> (`applyChgToBackground`, `colorRGBValueList`, or `colorStringList)`,  and then processes the semantically organized data.</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
  
